WEBVTT

00:02.880 --> 00:04.880
<i>He's a Chief inspector.</i>

00:04.960 --> 00:06.280
I reckon it's communists he's after.

00:06.720 --> 00:08.680
So this copper's going
to leave us alone, right?

00:08.920 --> 00:11.640
-What the fuck!
-(GROANING)

00:12.480 --> 00:15.480
I want you to see this as me
introducing myself to you.

00:16.320 --> 00:18.800
He said Mr Churchill sent him
to Birmingham.

00:18.880 --> 00:20.640
Something about a robbery.

00:21.440 --> 00:24.040
Thomas, you're a bookmaker.
You're not a fool.

00:24.480 --> 00:27.200
You sell these guns to anyone who has
use to them, you will hang.

00:27.880 --> 00:30.520
I'm just a poor communist frog
with a big mouth.

00:30.680 --> 00:33.600
I'm with you 'cause you're the
only man around here not scared of them.

00:34.320 --> 00:36.320
The only difference between
you and me, Freddie,

00:36.400 --> 00:39.800
is that, sometimes, my horses
stand a chance of winning.

00:40.200 --> 00:41.200
Tommy!

00:42.440 --> 00:43.720
You're fixing races now.

00:44.840 --> 00:46.440
GRACE:
<i>l'm here about the job as a barmaid.</i>

00:49.320 --> 00:50.320
Are you in position?

00:51.640 --> 00:52.640
I am, sir.

01:27.920 --> 01:33.160
<i># Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track</i>

01:35.640 --> 01:39.720
<i># Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

01:39.800 --> 01:43.760
<i># As it shifts and cracks</i>

01:43.840 --> 01:49.640
<i># Where secrets lie in the border fires
in the humming wires... #</i>

01:49.800 --> 01:52.000
I thought you said we were
going to the fair.

01:53.840 --> 01:57.440
We have business first.
Come on. Bring your wits.

01:57.800 --> 01:59.680
-What business?
-That's the Lee family.

02:00.880 --> 02:02.880
-Tommy!
-Johnny-dogs!

02:03.560 --> 02:05.160
Tommy, how the hell are ya?

02:05.240 --> 02:07.760
All the better for getting
the city smoke out of me lungs.

02:08.000 --> 02:10.120
I thought you became
a bit too grand for us.

02:10.200 --> 02:13.400
-I've been busy.
-I'm riding with the Lee family now.

02:13.920 --> 02:17.160
I heard. Myself, I'd rather
live among pigs.

02:17.560 --> 02:19.320
Come on, Tommy, no disputing.

02:20.200 --> 02:21.480
So your first fair since France?

02:22.520 --> 02:25.880
What do you know about France?
You war-shy, gypsy bastard.

02:27.480 --> 02:30.040
-So this is the horse?
-And that's the car.

02:45.200 --> 02:46.240
Hang on a minute.

02:47.280 --> 02:50.480
You're not swapping the family car
for a bloody horse.

02:50.680 --> 02:52.400
Of course we're not swapping it.

02:52.640 --> 02:54.440
Huh? That'd be mad.

02:54.520 --> 02:55.880
We're gonna play two up.

03:16.400 --> 03:18.320
-TOMMY: Here you are.
-Yeah, I knew it.

03:18.720 --> 03:21.240
See, I knew it. Tommy, you bloody idiot.

03:21.320 --> 03:22.600
Shut up, Arthur, I won.

03:22.880 --> 03:24.000
Oi!

03:24.080 --> 03:26.240
I promised Johnny I'd let him have
a spin in the car if he lost.

03:27.120 --> 03:29.000
-(MEN LAUGHING)
-All right.

03:33.680 --> 03:35.480
Are you Lee boys laughing at my brother?

03:38.320 --> 03:39.320
Are ya?

03:40.440 --> 03:42.640
-Eh?
-Tommy! Tommy, come on!

03:42.720 --> 03:45.640
-I asked you a question.
-Tommy, come on, it's just the craic.

03:46.480 --> 03:47.680
Get your family out of here,

03:47.760 --> 03:51.080
and go and enjoy yourselves at the fair
before they start a war. Huh?

03:51.160 --> 03:53.760
(SPEAKING FOREIGN LANGUAGE)

03:59.040 --> 04:01.240
Yeah, but his mum was a didicoy whore.

05:03.280 --> 05:05.080
(BELL TOLLING)

05:28.680 --> 05:31.640
We will take them
before last night's beer

05:32.040 --> 05:33.880
turns to piss and wakes the devils up.

05:35.280 --> 05:37.200
We will leave no stone unturned.

05:37.280 --> 05:40.760
Every gun, every bullet
will be brought to me for inspection.

05:41.880 --> 05:44.800
Now, take your positions.

06:06.640 --> 06:07.640
(ALL SHOUTING)

06:08.720 --> 06:09.720
(GROANING)

06:12.560 --> 06:16.680
(WOMAN SHOUTING)

06:17.800 --> 06:19.320
(BOTH MOANING)

06:22.080 --> 06:24.840
Freddie... (MOANING)

06:24.920 --> 06:25.920
(KNOCKING <i>AT</i> DOOR)

06:26.480 --> 06:28.160
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

06:29.040 --> 06:30.560
Are you sure your brothers
are at the fair?

06:30.640 --> 06:32.040
If it was them, they wouldn't knock.

06:32.560 --> 06:33.560
MAN: Mr Thorne!

06:34.880 --> 06:35.960
What is it?

06:36.040 --> 06:37.840
MAN: The police are rounding up
the communists.

06:39.360 --> 06:42.520
Come on, Ada. If the cops find me,
we're screwed. Fuck!

06:46.000 --> 06:47.080
Ada.

07:05.720 --> 07:07.840
You have to jump, Ada. I'll catch ya.

07:08.000 --> 07:09.000
Come on.

07:10.920 --> 07:11.920
(YELPS)

07:17.200 --> 07:18.200
Look at this.

07:19.040 --> 07:22.960
A prescription for iron tablets
for Ada fucking Shelby.

07:24.560 --> 07:25.600
(KNOCKING <i>AT</i> DOOR)

07:26.200 --> 07:28.880
Mrs Donovan, I need that favour.

07:28.960 --> 07:30.840
-Come in and be quick.
-I'm not coming in. She is.

07:31.120 --> 07:32.960
Holy Jesus! It's the Shelby girl.

07:33.120 --> 07:34.640
You've not seen her with me,
okay, Mrs Donovan?

07:34.720 --> 07:35.800
Just give her a cup of tea
and let her stay

07:35.880 --> 07:36.880
until the police are gone.

07:36.960 --> 07:39.720
She's the sister of those
Peaky Blinder devils.

07:39.800 --> 07:42.720
And, yet, she's an angel. Come on, Ada.

07:43.800 --> 07:45.160
What are you gonna do, Freddie?

07:45.240 --> 07:47.120
Me? I'm gonna have to leave town
for a bit.

07:50.520 --> 07:53.560
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

07:57.960 --> 07:59.960
(DOOR OPENING)

08:00.120 --> 08:01.560
(DOOR CLOSING)

08:05.320 --> 08:07.320
A gentleman would take off his hat.

08:09.240 --> 08:10.400
Put out his pipe.

08:19.480 --> 08:21.080
I see you Specials only dare come here

08:21.160 --> 08:23.040
when you know
the boys are away at the fair.

08:24.080 --> 08:25.280
You mean your nephews?

08:26.480 --> 08:30.360
With their guns and their razors?
Is it them you're lighting candles for?

08:31.840 --> 08:32.920
No.

08:33.800 --> 08:35.800
I'm lighting candles for the boys
from The Garrison

08:35.880 --> 08:37.760
who lost their lives in France.

08:39.320 --> 08:41.160
There's a list there.

08:42.760 --> 08:43.880
Look.

08:49.160 --> 08:51.640
I hear you didn't make it to France,

08:51.720 --> 08:52.800
Inspector Campbell.

08:56.240 --> 08:57.960
You've heard of me?

08:59.520 --> 09:00.720
I've heard of you.

09:04.560 --> 09:06.040
Is it the Holy Grail you're looking for?

09:07.080 --> 09:08.480
As a matter of fact,

09:09.000 --> 09:11.400
it is the Holy Grail I'm looking for.

09:11.920 --> 09:16.960
Something precious, something stolen.
Perhaps you know what I'm talking about.

09:20.360 --> 09:23.920
Sorry. I misunderstood your intention
when you pushed me against the wall.

09:37.200 --> 09:39.640
Turn the place upside down.

09:42.760 --> 09:44.880
Arthur Shelby said you people
would help us.

09:45.480 --> 09:47.520
If we don't know what you've lost,
how can we help you find it?

09:47.600 --> 09:50.440
But I have found out subsequently
that I was speaking to the wrong man.

09:50.760 --> 09:53.560
Next time, I want to talk to the boss.

09:55.000 --> 09:58.560
Lickey Tea Rooms. Friday, 10:00.

09:59.040 --> 10:01.360
And when I say "the boss,"
I mean Thomas.

10:07.240 --> 10:08.360
Come on.

10:34.400 --> 10:36.440
Now what the bloody hell's
been going on here?

10:39.240 --> 10:40.440
Jesus Christ.

10:41.000 --> 10:43.720
The coppers told everyone Arthur
had agreed to it when he was arrested.

10:44.320 --> 10:47.320
They said the Peaky Blinders had cleared
out to the fair to let them do it.

10:48.560 --> 10:50.200
No one never said nothing to that copper

10:50.280 --> 10:52.360
about smashing up bloody houses!

10:52.440 --> 10:54.560
All right. Which pubs did they do?

10:54.920 --> 10:56.920
The Guns, The Chain, The Marquis.

10:57.000 --> 10:58.920
All the ones that pay you
to protect them.

10:59.280 --> 11:01.440
The only one they didn't touch
was The Garrison.

11:03.000 --> 11:04.760
Made sure people think we were in on it.

11:06.000 --> 11:07.320
Smart, this copper.

11:09.200 --> 11:11.960
So go on. Drink your beers. Get out.

11:12.240 --> 11:14.720
You better show people
you'll still the cocks of the walk.

11:14.800 --> 11:17.200
Hand out some cash
to the landlords of the pubs.

11:17.280 --> 11:19.080
Pay some veterans to fix the places up.

11:19.480 --> 11:21.040
Give us the bag.

11:21.360 --> 11:23.000
So what about you, Tommy?

11:23.320 --> 11:26.080
I've to go to Charlie's
to stable the horse.

11:26.280 --> 11:27.960
Looked foot sore in the box.

11:31.920 --> 11:33.320
Let them see your faces.

11:42.240 --> 11:43.840
So we both know what
they were looking for.

11:50.400 --> 11:51.560
You don't read the papers?

11:52.200 --> 11:53.320
Racing papers.

11:54.280 --> 11:55.400
So let me tell you the odds.

11:56.520 --> 11:58.680
I reckon it's 3-to-1
there'll be a revolution.

11:59.440 --> 12:00.600
I wouldn't bet on that.

12:01.240 --> 12:02.320
That copper's betting on it.

12:03.520 --> 12:05.640
He's not gonna let it rest
till he gets those guns back.

12:12.480 --> 12:13.520
(SIGHS)

12:14.240 --> 12:15.600
Did he talk to ya, Pol?

12:17.480 --> 12:18.600
In the church.

12:20.000 --> 12:21.200
Did he try to find our Ada?

12:22.960 --> 12:24.120
She was sleeping.

12:24.880 --> 12:25.960
(SCOFFS)

12:27.800 --> 12:29.080
Where was she sleeping, Pol?

12:31.360 --> 12:33.360
I thought you didn't care
for women's business.

12:40.040 --> 12:41.440
He knows you're the boss.

12:42.040 --> 12:43.360
He wants to meet you.

12:49.880 --> 12:51.720
-Will you talk to him?
-No.

12:53.840 --> 12:55.400
You don't parlay when you're
on the back foot.

12:58.480 --> 13:00.400
We'll strike a blow back first.

13:16.680 --> 13:17.760
BARMAN: Hey, lad.

13:18.160 --> 13:20.480
-What are you doing?
-We're having a fire.

13:20.680 --> 13:21.880
(RAPID KNOCKING <i>AT</i> DOOR)

13:22.480 --> 13:24.000
Take off your picture of the King.

13:24.080 --> 13:25.080
What?

13:25.160 --> 13:26.560
-Bring it to Watery Lane.
-(COIN CLANGING)

13:27.520 --> 13:30.440
(MEN TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

13:31.040 --> 13:32.040
(LAUGHING)

13:39.360 --> 13:40.480
(ALL CHEERING)

13:48.840 --> 13:49.960
Chuck them on, boys.

13:50.520 --> 13:51.520
-(ALL CHEERING)
-ALL: Yeah!

13:55.600 --> 13:57.640
Well, I hope to God you
know what you're doing.

13:59.640 --> 14:00.720
(ALL CHEERING)

14:18.320 --> 14:19.440
I'm the reporter.

14:19.720 --> 14:21.280
The <i>Birmingham Evening Despatch.</i>

14:22.080 --> 14:23.160
I had a phone call.

14:24.200 --> 14:25.960
Someone called Thomas Shelby?

14:26.760 --> 14:28.040
Come with me.

14:30.120 --> 14:33.000
Move aside. Give us a bit of room.
Tommy.

14:34.440 --> 14:36.080
Move back for us, please, folks.

14:36.240 --> 14:37.280
You're Mr Shelby?

14:37.360 --> 14:38.680
-MAN: All the way back, please.
-I am.

14:42.000 --> 14:43.560
You said I would be protected.

14:44.120 --> 14:45.560
You're protected.

14:46.640 --> 14:47.960
What's going on?

14:48.520 --> 14:50.560
There are some things I want you
to write down.

14:52.600 --> 14:53.840
Now, first of all.

14:54.400 --> 14:57.000
It's not the people around here
that are disloyal to the King.

14:57.560 --> 14:59.080
It's the opposite.

14:59.720 --> 15:01.360
You see, we don't want our beloved king

15:01.440 --> 15:03.880
looking down and seeing the things
that have been done to us.

15:04.720 --> 15:06.560
So we are taking down his pictures.

15:06.640 --> 15:08.080
But why are you burning them?

15:09.120 --> 15:11.880
We went through hell for our king.

15:12.320 --> 15:15.040
Walked through the flames of war.
Write all this down!

15:15.480 --> 15:17.720
And now we're being attacked
in our own homes.

15:18.880 --> 15:21.080
These new coppers over from Belfast,

15:21.240 --> 15:23.720
breaking into our homes
and interfering with our women.

15:23.920 --> 15:26.320
We don't think our king
would want to see that happening.

15:27.720 --> 15:29.760
So we are lighting fires
to raise the alarm.

15:30.840 --> 15:33.680
May I ask you,
in what capacity do you speak?

15:34.280 --> 15:35.360
No capacity.

15:36.320 --> 15:37.360
I'm an ordinary man.

15:38.120 --> 15:39.960
I won gallantry medals at the Somme.

15:41.360 --> 15:43.640
I want you to write in your paper
what's going on here.

15:45.800 --> 15:46.920
Go on, go.

15:55.680 --> 15:56.760
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

15:56.840 --> 15:57.920
Come in.

15:58.000 --> 15:59.080
(DOOR OPENING)

16:00.920 --> 16:02.480
MAN: There... There...

16:03.040 --> 16:06.200
There's a telephone call for you, sir,
on the London line.

16:06.280 --> 16:08.400
There is? It's almost midnight.

16:09.640 --> 16:11.280
It's Mr Winston Churchill, sir.

16:24.480 --> 16:26.560
-Yes, sir.
-Inspector Campbell.

16:26.920 --> 16:29.360
I hear there's been a bonfire
in your city.

16:29.880 --> 16:33.360
There was a small fire reported
around 9:00 in Watery Lane.

16:33.800 --> 16:35.520
<i>Certainly nothing to trouble
you about, sir.</i>

16:35.760 --> 16:38.080
Ah, but I'm afraid it has troubled me.

16:38.760 --> 16:42.120
Half an hour ago,
I received a wire communication

16:42.200 --> 16:45.080
from the editor of the
<i>Birmingham Evening Despatch.</i>

16:46.160 --> 16:49.560
<i>It seems one of his reporters
was invited to the fire</i>

16:49.640 --> 16:53.000
<i>and discovered that they were burning
pictures of the King.</i>

16:53.640 --> 16:54.680
Of the King?

16:55.400 --> 16:58.560
Any newspaper report
which may cause embarrassment

16:58.640 --> 17:01.200
to His Majesty is always referred first,

17:01.280 --> 17:03.960
and as a matter of routine,
to the Home Office.

17:04.320 --> 17:06.800
I will go down there immediately,
and, er, arrest those involved.

17:07.600 --> 17:10.840
No, you most certainly will not
make arrests.

17:11.280 --> 17:13.600
<i>If there are arrests,
there will be trials.</i>

17:13.680 --> 17:17.240
If there are trials, there will be
more newspaper reports

17:17.320 --> 17:21.520
which will necessarily mention
the burning of the King's likeness.

17:22.040 --> 17:26.320
I put you in Birmingham
for one very specific reason.

17:26.760 --> 17:30.400
Are you any nearer to finding
those stolen guns?

17:30.600 --> 17:32.760
-We are making steady progress.
-We need results.

17:32.840 --> 17:34.960
Goodnight, Mr Campbell.

17:35.040 --> 17:37.360
<i>Sir...</i> (CLEARS THROAT)
<i>Could I at least ask...</i>

17:37.440 --> 17:40.520
Does this report
name any of those involved?

17:41.520 --> 17:43.520
It names a Mr Thomas Shelby.

17:44.000 --> 17:46.160
The report mentions he's a war hero.

17:46.680 --> 17:47.760
(PHONE LINE CUTS OUT)

17:57.440 --> 17:58.640
Good of you to join us.

17:59.800 --> 18:01.640
-Where have you been all day?
-ADA: In bed.

18:02.960 --> 18:06.120
Couldn't sleep. Then I couldn't wake up.

18:06.680 --> 18:09.280
Then I was cold, and then
I had to go for a wee.

18:10.160 --> 18:12.880
Then I was with this bear on a boat.

18:12.960 --> 18:16.600
That was just a dream.
Then I was hungry.

18:17.360 --> 18:18.640
Why are you reading the paper?

18:20.320 --> 18:21.400
Why wouldn't I be?

18:21.480 --> 18:23.280
Well, I've never seen you
read the paper.

18:23.360 --> 18:25.440
I've only ever seen you
light fires with them.

18:25.800 --> 18:29.520
The BSA on strike. Miners are on strike.

18:30.120 --> 18:31.840
IRA are killing our boys.

18:32.320 --> 18:33.440
Ten a day.

18:37.160 --> 18:38.160
What?

18:39.160 --> 18:40.160
Stand up.

18:40.760 --> 18:42.440
-Why?
-Just stand up.

18:49.480 --> 18:50.680
Side on.

18:52.600 --> 18:54.120
Oi, what are you doing?

18:54.800 --> 18:55.920
Ada,

18:57.680 --> 18:58.760
how late are you?

19:01.920 --> 19:03.000
One week.

19:05.600 --> 19:07.040
Five weeks.

19:07.800 --> 19:10.720
Seven, if you count weekends.
I think it's a lack of iron.

19:11.760 --> 19:12.960
I got some tablets.

19:14.120 --> 19:15.320
But they didn't work.

19:18.920 --> 19:20.040
No.

19:29.560 --> 19:31.200
WOMAN: You can get dressed now, love.

19:32.600 --> 19:33.960
So, am I or not?

19:41.040 --> 19:43.800
Keep bloody walking, Ada.
If anybody sees us here, they'll know.

19:43.880 --> 19:45.080
I'm not getting rid of it, Aunt Pol.

19:45.560 --> 19:46.840
Just come home and we'll talk about it.

19:46.960 --> 19:48.920
You get off of me,
or I'll scream it, I swear.

19:53.760 --> 19:56.000
All right, you want to do this
on the street? Let's do it.

19:56.480 --> 19:57.760
Whose is it?

19:57.840 --> 20:00.800
If I tell you, you'll tell them
and they'll cut him to pieces.

20:01.920 --> 20:03.720
Not if he marries you, they won't.

20:06.600 --> 20:08.240
Will he marry you?

20:09.600 --> 20:11.040
I don't know. I don't know where he is.

20:11.120 --> 20:12.160
Jesus Christ, Ada!

20:12.240 --> 20:13.800
Look, he's gone away
but he said he'd come back.

20:13.880 --> 20:15.080
Yeah, but they all say
they'll come back.

20:15.360 --> 20:18.000
He's not like that,
he's a good man, he promised.

20:19.880 --> 20:22.160
He will come back, Aunt Pol,
I know he will.

20:22.520 --> 20:23.640
(SOBBING)

20:31.000 --> 20:32.760
Get me down a Spanish saddle, Joe.

20:33.880 --> 20:35.880
Yes, Tom. A Spanish saddle...
He's a beauty, Tom.

20:36.640 --> 20:38.440
Yeah, yeah... Beautiful. Yeah.

20:44.600 --> 20:46.400
Fine beast you got there, Thomas.

20:48.480 --> 20:51.000
But is he worth falling out
with the Lee family over?

21:03.720 --> 21:04.840
Just passing it on.

21:06.560 --> 21:09.280
Declaration of war. The whole Lee clan.

21:15.600 --> 21:18.520
The guns and now this.

21:19.760 --> 21:22.520
The guns are not spoken of.

21:23.680 --> 21:24.760
Right?

21:27.600 --> 21:29.960
Tommy. Tommy!

21:33.280 --> 21:34.640
You mind how to speak to me.

21:34.800 --> 21:36.240
(SCOFFS) Forgive me, Uncle.

21:42.080 --> 21:45.080
It's Thomas Shelby against
the whole bloody world, right?

21:46.680 --> 21:47.800
(CLICKS TONGUE)

22:10.440 --> 22:11.440
(WHINNYING)

22:11.600 --> 22:14.400
(EXPLOSIONS)

22:15.880 --> 22:17.320
Easy! Easy!

22:20.720 --> 22:24.080
Easy, boy. (SHUSHING)

22:25.160 --> 22:27.480
Shh. In France, we used to say...

22:28.080 --> 22:31.800
Shh. In France we used to say it's just
the musical hall band turning up.

22:32.400 --> 22:34.720
Shh. It's just trombones
and tubas, that's all.

22:35.320 --> 22:37.240
It's just noise. Shh. Shh. Shh.

22:39.480 --> 22:42.280
It's just noise, all right?
It's just noise.

22:43.480 --> 22:44.640
You get used to it.

22:45.280 --> 22:47.600
It's just noise. Good boy.

22:48.040 --> 22:49.040
Good boy.

23:01.840 --> 23:03.600
In some pain there, boy, eh?

23:09.080 --> 23:10.680
I... I'm so sorry, Mr Shelby.

23:13.880 --> 23:16.200
-I'm Grace, by the way.
-I know who you are.

23:18.920 --> 23:20.040
What's his name?

23:20.680 --> 23:22.120
He doesn't have a name.

23:22.840 --> 23:24.080
Poor boy, deserves a name.

23:25.920 --> 23:27.280
Do you have something to say to me?

23:31.120 --> 23:33.360
The other night you came into the pub
when I was singing.

23:35.000 --> 23:36.680
You said singing wasn't allowed.

23:38.880 --> 23:40.920
I'd like there to be one night a week
when there's singing.

23:43.880 --> 23:45.200
I think it would be good for everyone.

23:46.200 --> 23:47.400
Saturday nights.

23:49.520 --> 23:51.360
Harry was too afraid to ask you so...

23:52.800 --> 23:54.000
But you're not?

23:57.480 --> 23:58.560
I am.

24:00.040 --> 24:01.120
But I love to sing.

24:04.480 --> 24:06.040
You sound like one of those rich girls

24:06.120 --> 24:08.320
who comes over from Dublin
for the races.

24:09.640 --> 24:10.760
Do you like horses?

24:13.720 --> 24:15.280
How'd you fancy
earning some extra money?

24:15.760 --> 24:16.800
Doing what?

24:17.160 --> 24:18.280
(SIGHS)

24:19.480 --> 24:20.680
Dig out a nice dress.

24:22.120 --> 24:23.480
I want to take you to the races.

24:34.920 --> 24:36.960
(MEN BETTING INDISTINCTLY)

24:37.040 --> 24:40.400
Go a couple of charges coming in, John.
Rock Ferry down two-eighths.

24:40.760 --> 24:44.640
(MEN BETTING INDISTINCTLY)

25:06.480 --> 25:08.960
Sorry, Mr Shelby. Go on!

25:15.880 --> 25:18.040
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

25:18.160 --> 25:21.040
-All right, Mr Shelby. How's it going?
-Hello, Frank. How's the leg?

25:21.120 --> 25:22.680
-Not bad.
-Good.

25:22.760 --> 25:24.280
Nice to see you, son.

25:25.920 --> 25:27.120
Morning, Charlie.

25:28.240 --> 25:29.440
The odds are good, boss.

25:29.680 --> 25:31.560
-How are we looking?
-Looking good, Tommy.

25:31.640 --> 25:32.960
Tommy? Tommy?

25:33.120 --> 25:34.840
They're all here for Monaghan Boy.

25:34.920 --> 25:36.440
That's what I like to hear, Johnny boy.

25:36.800 --> 25:38.080
And Aunt Pol wants to see ya.

26:31.520 --> 26:32.680
(SIGHS)

26:42.720 --> 26:43.800
(SIGHS)

26:44.560 --> 26:46.160
Tell me the man's name, Ada.

26:47.560 --> 26:49.280
Rudolph Valentino.

27:09.640 --> 27:10.720
Get out!

27:11.360 --> 27:12.440
All of you.

27:12.800 --> 27:14.360
-Go on. Now!
-(DOOR OPENING)

27:18.160 --> 27:19.760
I said tell me his fucking name.

27:23.960 --> 27:26.400
Freddie fucking Thorne!

27:28.920 --> 27:34.120
Yeah. Your best mate since school,
the man who saved your life in France.

27:34.680 --> 27:36.640
So, go on. Go and cut him.

27:37.240 --> 27:39.520
Cut him up and chuck him in the cut.

27:42.720 --> 27:45.080
Oi! I'm a Shelby, too, you know!

27:45.400 --> 27:47.320
Put my fucking film back on.

28:20.920 --> 28:23.000
So Monaghan Boy finally lost?

28:25.480 --> 28:26.600
Third time unlucky.

28:28.480 --> 28:30.040
We took money from all over the city.

28:30.120 --> 28:32.080
Yeah, but you'll pay it back
to people round here.

28:33.720 --> 28:35.040
Buy your popularity back.

28:35.760 --> 28:36.840
Already done.

28:37.560 --> 28:38.680
Taught you well.

28:40.160 --> 28:42.760
And you fixed this race
without the permission of Billy Kimber?

28:43.680 --> 28:44.720
(SCOFFS)

28:45.680 --> 28:47.400
Obviously didn't teach you well enough!

28:47.680 --> 28:49.840
Rule one. You don't punch
above your weight.

28:50.160 --> 28:52.640
-Billy Kimber is there for the taking.
-Says who?

28:53.240 --> 28:54.880
Says Tom and his parliament of one.

28:55.800 --> 28:58.280
-I ran this business for five years.
-Yeah.

28:58.720 --> 29:00.280
While I was away fighting, remember?

29:00.680 --> 29:02.280
Where I learned some things, such as

29:02.560 --> 29:03.960
you strike when the enemy is weak.

29:06.240 --> 29:08.640
And I thought you came here
to talk family business.

29:10.240 --> 29:13.280
I'll deal with it.
You're too busy taking over the world.

29:13.360 --> 29:14.440
Polly.

29:15.480 --> 29:17.160
It's about Ada. I need to know.

29:25.240 --> 29:27.120
Ada wants you to give
Freddie this letter.

29:29.080 --> 29:30.680
She wants Freddie to know
she's having his baby.

29:31.200 --> 29:33.360
He deserves an opportunity
to do the right thing.

29:34.600 --> 29:35.760
I say we give them a chance.

29:37.280 --> 29:38.360
(SIGHS)

29:42.160 --> 29:44.280
For a woman who's had a hard life of men,

29:44.360 --> 29:46.520
you're still full of romance, eh?

29:48.080 --> 29:50.560
What do you think Freddie sees
in our Ada?

29:50.640 --> 29:51.880
-That's Freddie's business.
-No.

29:52.400 --> 29:53.800
No, I'll tell you what he sees.

29:54.160 --> 29:59.960
He sees machine guns and rifles and
ammunition and some glorious revolution.

30:00.040 --> 30:01.800
What is it you really don't like
about Freddie?

30:02.880 --> 30:04.600
She'll have no life with a
man on the run.

30:05.080 --> 30:06.400
If you can't see that,
you can't see much.

30:12.800 --> 30:14.720
Damn them for what they
did to you in France!

30:18.080 --> 30:20.720
Tell Ada Freddie went to America.

30:21.840 --> 30:22.960
Or Russia.

30:23.800 --> 30:26.800
Polly, it'd do no good for Ada
to bring a baby into the world alone.

30:27.400 --> 30:30.880
Pol, listen. The truth is you would've
hit me with that thing

30:30.960 --> 30:33.000
if it weren't for the fact
that you know I'm right!

30:39.560 --> 30:40.800
Thought I heard someone knocking.

30:42.400 --> 30:43.480
Couldn't get back to sleep.

30:47.720 --> 30:49.320
POLLY: The longer you leave it,

30:50.280 --> 30:51.880
the worse it gets.

30:59.400 --> 31:00.720
Believe me.

31:01.440 --> 31:02.880
I know.

31:05.200 --> 31:06.760
I was 16.

31:09.280 --> 31:11.160
And I didn't dare tell anyone.

31:12.240 --> 31:13.720
Polly, Freddie'll come back.

31:14.760 --> 31:16.360
In the end, I did it myself.

31:18.880 --> 31:20.760
I did it to myself.

31:21.400 --> 31:22.920
And I almost died.

31:24.080 --> 31:25.360
And he didn't come back.

31:26.360 --> 31:27.960
They don't. Why should they?

31:29.440 --> 31:31.040
You know the words.

31:31.120 --> 31:33.360
You're a whore. Baby's a bastard.

31:34.400 --> 31:36.800
But there's no word for the man
who doesn't come back.

31:40.840 --> 31:41.920
One day,

31:42.800 --> 31:44.400
on your wedding day,

31:45.240 --> 31:47.280
you'll have a good man on your arm.

31:48.600 --> 31:49.800
And you'll say, "Polly,

31:50.640 --> 31:51.720
"thank you,

31:52.080 --> 31:53.200
"for common sense."

32:02.640 --> 32:04.400
This woman's in Cardiff.

32:05.800 --> 32:07.480
We'll take the train tomorrow.

32:11.280 --> 32:13.040
Go to the castle afterwards for a treat.

33:07.320 --> 33:09.120
I chose this place because

33:09.920 --> 33:12.080
it is outside both of our jurisdictions.

33:14.440 --> 33:15.520
Do you want tea?

33:17.760 --> 33:19.880
Inspector, I responded
to your invitation

33:19.960 --> 33:21.640
because I want us
to understand each other.

33:23.520 --> 33:24.760
I'm a businessman.

33:26.080 --> 33:28.080
I want to make my business successful.

33:29.360 --> 33:31.320
And I want my city run peacefully.

33:32.760 --> 33:35.320
Well, if the city is peaceful,
business can thrive.

33:37.440 --> 33:39.040
So we're on the same side.

33:41.000 --> 33:42.280
I think perhaps we could be.

33:49.600 --> 33:50.720
My...

33:54.720 --> 33:58.520
How can we be on the same side
when I see things like this?

34:00.760 --> 34:02.560
My men found this

34:03.400 --> 34:04.480
in the bedroom

34:05.160 --> 34:06.880
of a known communist.

34:08.120 --> 34:09.880
It has your sister's name on it.

34:12.160 --> 34:14.840
It was obvious she'd been
sleeping in his bed.

34:16.320 --> 34:20.640
Are you also in bed
with the communists, Mr Shelby?

34:21.600 --> 34:23.120
I do not share their fantasy.

34:24.480 --> 34:26.200
And as for my sister,

34:26.400 --> 34:28.080
I've already dealt with the situation.

34:29.480 --> 34:31.680
Freddie Thorne is at the very top
of my list.

34:31.760 --> 34:33.000
Well, cross him off.

34:34.160 --> 34:35.720
He won't be returning to the city.

34:37.840 --> 34:40.000
I'll make him part of our deal.

34:41.560 --> 34:42.920
What deal?

34:47.360 --> 34:50.480
You and your Specials will leave
my businesses alone from now on.

34:51.520 --> 34:54.640
No more raids into our territory,
no more smashing our pubs.

34:55.040 --> 34:56.400
No more lifting my runners.

34:56.800 --> 35:00.640
You will turn a blind eye
to all of my gambling operations. Also,

35:02.000 --> 35:03.280
I am planning an expansion

35:03.960 --> 35:05.400
onto the race tracks.

35:05.960 --> 35:08.120
I intend to do business
with Billy Kimber.

35:09.080 --> 35:11.840
He runs most of the legal track side
betting outside of London.

35:12.960 --> 35:14.440
He has policemen on his payroll.

35:15.240 --> 35:18.840
I want you to put in a word with
the Chief Inspector of Gloucestershire,

35:19.480 --> 35:21.560
that his men should leave me alone

35:21.800 --> 35:23.600
when I make my move.

35:26.440 --> 35:28.280
Forgive me, I don't seem to have a pen

35:28.680 --> 35:31.640
to write down this rather
long list of demands.

35:35.520 --> 35:36.960
And what do I get in return?

35:39.120 --> 35:40.520
I have what you're looking for.

35:46.640 --> 35:48.080
I have the guns.

35:50.480 --> 35:51.560
What guns?

35:51.960 --> 35:53.880
-I'm not here to play games.
-Wait, wait...

36:06.000 --> 36:08.560
Twenty five Lewis machine guns.
Fifty carbines.

36:08.960 --> 36:10.960
Ten thousand rounds of ammunition.

36:11.160 --> 36:13.160
All in a crate bound for Libya.

36:13.640 --> 36:15.920
Stolen from the BSA
factory proofing bay.

36:17.880 --> 36:20.560
I'm guessing they sent you to Birmingham
to get those guns back.

36:21.240 --> 36:22.600
Well,

36:22.960 --> 36:24.160
it's me that has them.

36:26.840 --> 36:28.840
I have left word with men I trust,

36:28.920 --> 36:31.600
that if I am taken into police custody
for whatever reason,

36:32.040 --> 36:33.800
those guns will be shipped to Liverpool.

36:34.400 --> 36:36.680
From there, they will be sent
directly to Belfast.

36:37.000 --> 36:39.760
And sold to the Irish Republican Army.

36:41.200 --> 36:43.160
All your good work in Ireland
will be undone.

36:43.960 --> 36:46.000
Each stolen weapon
is numbered and marked.

36:46.600 --> 36:50.240
If I sell them to the IRA, it won't
be long before Mr Churchill finds out.

36:51.240 --> 36:52.520
I imagine you got into enough trouble

36:52.600 --> 36:54.400
over the burning
of the King's photographs.

36:55.840 --> 36:57.040
That was just a taster.

36:57.960 --> 36:59.680
If those guns reach Belfast,

37:01.080 --> 37:03.120
your life in the force is over.

37:04.720 --> 37:07.200
When I have achieved
what I have set out to achieve,

37:07.840 --> 37:09.520
I will let you know where
to find the guns.

37:10.480 --> 37:11.560
You'll be a hero.

37:12.040 --> 37:13.880
You'll probably get a medal.

37:16.560 --> 37:17.640
I'm a fair man.

37:18.880 --> 37:19.960
It's a fair offer.

37:22.560 --> 37:23.680
Do we have a deal?

37:32.680 --> 37:33.920
I need an answer.

37:34.800 --> 37:35.960
Right now.

37:40.800 --> 37:41.960
Very well.

37:44.360 --> 37:47.200
But I'd prefer if we don't
shake hands on it.

38:01.200 --> 38:03.040
Now, why would I shake the hand of a man

38:03.920 --> 38:05.680
who didn't even fight for his country?

38:19.800 --> 38:23.880
(SINGING PUCCINI'S <i>TOSCA)</i>

38:45.160 --> 38:46.280
(KNOCKING)

38:50.200 --> 38:51.320
Grace.

38:57.280 --> 38:59.800
I have new information.

39:03.120 --> 39:04.800
Thomas Shelby is now the beginning,

39:05.920 --> 39:07.760
the middle and the end of your mission.

39:20.760 --> 39:21.920
So what shall I do?

39:23.800 --> 39:25.520
It hurts me as much as it...

39:26.400 --> 39:29.920
As it would a father sending
his own daughter into a whorehouse.

39:33.120 --> 39:35.440
But no matter how repugnant it may be,

39:36.920 --> 39:39.400
you must do everything you can

39:39.480 --> 39:40.600
to get close to him.

39:41.800 --> 39:42.880
<i>And...</i>

39:43.920 --> 39:45.400
<i>Find out where those guns are hidden.</i>

39:49.000 --> 39:50.080
Of course, when I say

39:50.680 --> 39:51.720
everything, I don't mean...

39:53.800 --> 39:56.360
You underestimate me in every way.

40:06.160 --> 40:07.280
Here.

40:17.960 --> 40:20.960
You are now active
on a military operation

40:21.040 --> 40:22.680
on behalf of the Crown.

40:24.680 --> 40:28.080
And I wish to God
circumstance hadn't chosen you.

40:30.400 --> 40:32.280
It's what I'm trained for.

40:33.320 --> 40:35.200
I'm late for my shift.

40:39.360 --> 40:40.440
Grace,

40:42.320 --> 40:43.800
my heart is with you.

41:00.560 --> 41:01.720
Ahhh!

41:43.280 --> 41:46.400
Tom! Tom! Tom!

41:46.760 --> 41:48.360
You'd better come quick, Tom! Tom!

42:17.160 --> 42:18.240
Curly, tell me.

42:19.160 --> 42:20.240
Cursed, Tom.

42:23.240 --> 42:25.480
Curly, Curly... Shh. Shh. Shh.
Curly, Curly.

42:27.040 --> 42:29.960
Tell me. Tell me, Curly.
What's wrong with the horse?

42:30.960 --> 42:32.800
You bought at the fair in bad feeling.

42:33.160 --> 42:36.680
The Lees put a bad seed in the hoof
and got an old woman to put a spell.

42:41.800 --> 42:43.800
So those Lee bastards cursed him.

42:45.640 --> 42:47.000
Whatever it is, he says it

42:47.400 --> 42:48.840
spread to the other feet.

42:49.200 --> 42:51.440
It's going to his heart
by tomorrow, I say!

42:52.160 --> 42:55.240
I've seen curses like this twice.
Can't take them back, Tom.

42:55.720 --> 42:56.800
No.

42:57.640 --> 42:58.800
I told you, Tommy.

42:59.960 --> 43:02.560
Better enemies to have
than black blood gypsies.

43:06.560 --> 43:07.640
Get out.

43:09.160 --> 43:10.480
Get out, Curly.

43:16.720 --> 43:17.840
I'm sorry.

43:29.400 --> 43:31.280
(GUNSHOT)

43:47.400 --> 43:48.520
(BANGING ON DOOR)

43:57.000 --> 43:58.640
We're closed, Mr Shelby.

43:59.280 --> 44:00.800
Just get me a drink.

44:08.360 --> 44:10.400
(COUGHING)

44:14.560 --> 44:16.160
Shall I leave you alone?

44:17.920 --> 44:19.360
Came here for company.

44:20.760 --> 44:21.920
Where's Harry?

44:22.360 --> 44:23.560
He took the night off.

44:26.560 --> 44:28.200
Went to the pictures.

44:35.520 --> 44:36.640
How's your beautiful horse?

44:47.000 --> 44:48.680
I just put a bullet in his head.

44:53.200 --> 44:54.280
Was he lame?

44:57.680 --> 44:59.280
He looked at me the wrong way.

45:01.080 --> 45:04.280
It's not a good idea
to look at Tommy Shelby the wrong way.

45:09.840 --> 45:11.520
-What a waste.
-Yeah.

45:12.080 --> 45:14.120
A waste is what it is.

45:20.640 --> 45:21.720
You know, in France...

45:26.720 --> 45:29.080
In France, I got used to seeing men die.

45:31.280 --> 45:33.080
Never got used to seeing horses die.

45:35.680 --> 45:36.760
They die badly.

45:44.120 --> 45:45.760
I dug out a dress like you asked.

45:47.480 --> 45:48.760
Thanks.

45:51.000 --> 45:52.880
It's Cheltenham you're talking about.

46:00.600 --> 46:02.240
Cheltenham's a grand affair, is it not?

46:02.920 --> 46:04.120
The King will be there.

46:04.640 --> 46:06.280
-King George?
-No.

46:08.160 --> 46:11.000
King Billy Kimber. And all his men.

46:14.040 --> 46:15.160
And what must I do?

46:15.800 --> 46:18.080
For £2, you'll do what I ask you to do.

46:20.240 --> 46:21.280
I want three.

46:21.840 --> 46:22.960
(SCOFFS)

46:23.320 --> 46:26.200
If I'm meeting a king,
I won't be wearing a cheap dress.

46:30.040 --> 46:31.440
And I ask you to let me sing.

46:32.160 --> 46:33.240
It's part of the deal now, too.

46:35.120 --> 46:36.280
Since when?

46:38.600 --> 46:39.880
Since you nearly smiled.

46:45.000 --> 46:46.840
Saturday nights. Open and easy.

46:47.640 --> 46:49.880
Everyone gets to sing their song,
just like we did in Dublin.

46:50.120 --> 46:51.400
You never worked in Dublin.

46:52.560 --> 46:54.040
So don't lie to me.

46:54.880 --> 46:58.200
I asked around about that pub
you said you used to work in.

46:58.840 --> 47:00.440
I have friends over there.

47:01.400 --> 47:02.880
No one has heard of you.

47:09.600 --> 47:10.800
My guess is,

47:12.120 --> 47:13.800
you're a girl from a good family

47:14.600 --> 47:15.920
who got herself pregnant.

47:19.720 --> 47:21.080
It's not something I want known.

47:21.520 --> 47:24.120
And bringing a child into the
world alone ruined your life.

47:26.120 --> 47:27.520
Right?

47:31.240 --> 47:32.520
So I'm right.

47:33.280 --> 47:34.520
And Polly is wrong.

47:36.120 --> 47:37.640
Right about what?

47:38.400 --> 47:40.000
Doesn't matter.

47:41.280 --> 47:42.680
Looks like it matters to you.

47:43.880 --> 47:45.680
Family business.

47:49.480 --> 47:50.960
You won't tell anyone my secret?

47:52.600 --> 47:54.640
Do you think I tell people things?

47:58.840 --> 48:00.400
So what do you sing?

48:02.280 --> 48:03.960
-Anything you want.
-Right.

48:05.480 --> 48:06.640
Get up on the chair.

48:08.000 --> 48:09.120
Okay.

48:16.440 --> 48:17.520
Happy or sad?

48:21.560 --> 48:22.640
Sad.

48:24.240 --> 48:26.600
Okay. But I warn you,

48:27.480 --> 48:28.560
it'll break your heart.

48:30.040 --> 48:31.520
Already broken.

48:36.440 --> 48:40.880
<i># In a neat little town
they call Belfast</i>

48:42.240 --> 48:45.440
<i># Apprenticed to a trade I was bound</i>

48:46.960 --> 48:51.680
<i># Many an hours sweet happiness</i>

48:52.880 --> 48:57.480
<i># Had I spent
in that neat little town</i>

48:58.920 --> 49:03.880
<i># A sad misfortune came over me</i>

49:04.480 --> 49:08.280
<i># Which caused me
to stray from the land</i>

49:10.440 --> 49:12.440
<i># Faraway</i>

49:13.480 --> 49:17.240
<i># From my friends and relations</i>

49:19.240 --> 49:21.080
<i># Betrayed</i>

49:22.200 --> 49:25.160
<i># By the black velvet band</i>

49:26.560 --> 49:30.760
<i># Her eyes they shone like diamonds</i>

49:31.640 --> 49:35.400
<i># I thought her the queen of the land</i>

49:37.320 --> 49:42.640
<i># And her hair hung over her shoulder</i>

49:43.600 --> 49:45.320
<i># Tied up</i>

49:46.440 --> 49:49.240
<i># With a black velvet band #</i>

50:07.040 --> 50:08.160
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATION)

50:09.520 --> 50:10.600
-You okay?
-Yeah, I'm fine.

50:12.480 --> 50:15.280
I think there are some more carriages
over there that are gonna be empty.

50:16.520 --> 50:17.640
Jesus.

50:19.560 --> 50:20.640
Freddie.

50:21.440 --> 50:22.880
You came back?

50:25.600 --> 50:26.800
I got a tip-off.

50:27.560 --> 50:28.720
Freddie, Tommy will kill you.

50:28.960 --> 50:30.360
It's Tommy who tipped me off.

50:31.120 --> 50:32.880
Maybe he's got half a heart, after all.

50:34.320 --> 50:35.600
Tommy got a message to me.

50:36.760 --> 50:39.160
Said, "Get out of town.
Take her with you."

50:41.360 --> 50:42.480
So...

50:46.200 --> 50:47.600
Ada Shelby,

50:50.600 --> 50:51.760
will you marry me?

50:53.560 --> 50:54.680
Yes.

50:55.280 --> 50:56.400
Yes.

50:58.320 --> 50:59.440
Yes!

51:09.920 --> 51:11.000
(GIGGLES)

51:14.760 --> 51:17.320
Right. Get on this bloody train
and get out of here.

51:17.400 --> 51:18.440
(WHISTLE BLOWING)

51:18.520 --> 51:20.240
-Come on, both of you.
-Freddie, come on.

51:20.440 --> 51:24.360
Freddie... Cardiff's okay,
anywhere but here's okay.

51:24.960 --> 51:27.040
We're not going anywhere, Ada.

51:29.160 --> 51:31.000
We're gonna stay here,
we're gonna marry here.

51:33.120 --> 51:34.760
I'm not afraid of Tommy Shelby.

51:45.120 --> 51:48.400
(MEN SINGING <i>THE SUNSHINE OF YOUR SMILE)</i>

51:59.240 --> 52:01.600
(TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

52:02.280 --> 52:03.800
GRACE: Did you want whisky as well?

52:03.880 --> 52:05.400
No, just beer.

52:05.800 --> 52:08.120
Why no whisky, Tom.
You expecting trouble?

52:11.360 --> 52:14.320
Jesus Christ, Tommy, what the hell
made you let them sing?

52:14.880 --> 52:17.000
They sound like they're strangling cats
out there.

52:17.400 --> 52:20.040
All right. Twenty's the play, come on.

52:20.600 --> 52:24.320
Now, what did make you change
your mind though, Tommy? Hmm?

52:24.520 --> 52:26.400
(INDISTINCT)

52:26.520 --> 52:29.160
-It's about time, Tommy.
-Time for what?

52:29.560 --> 52:30.680
Well...

52:30.760 --> 52:33.760
-Time you took yourself a woman.
-Just play the bloody hand.

52:34.600 --> 52:36.320
You stay the way you are, Tommy.

52:36.640 --> 52:38.040
Remember what Dad used to say.

52:38.640 --> 52:42.240
-Fast women and slow horses...
-ALL: Will ruin your life.

52:43.520 --> 52:45.440
-JOHN: Coppers.
-No.

52:47.280 --> 52:50.840
<i># Come, Josephine, in my flying machine</i>

52:50.920 --> 52:52.960
<i># Going up, she goes</i>

52:53.160 --> 52:54.760
<i># Up she goes</i>

52:54.920 --> 52:58.240
<i># Balance yourself like a bird on a beam</i>

52:58.320 --> 53:00.120
<i># In the air she goes</i>

53:00.200 --> 53:02.200
<i># There she goes... #</i>

53:05.440 --> 53:06.920
(SINGING STOPS)

53:08.360 --> 53:09.560
Holy shit!

53:10.720 --> 53:11.840
It's Billy Kimber.

53:21.120 --> 53:23.280
Is there any man here named Shelby?

53:29.480 --> 53:30.760
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

53:31.200 --> 53:34.960
I said, "Is there any man here
named Shelby?"

53:41.560 --> 53:42.680
Harry, get these men a drink.

53:43.280 --> 53:44.680
Everyone else go home.

53:58.400 --> 53:59.480
You go home.

53:59.960 --> 54:02.480
-But Mr Fenton said...
-I said go home.

54:05.480 --> 54:08.560
I've never approved of women in pubs
but when they look like that...

54:09.080 --> 54:11.160
You said you want men called Shelby.

54:11.720 --> 54:13.360
You've got three of them.

54:14.120 --> 54:16.840
Right, I never heard of ya.
And then I did hear of ya,

54:16.920 --> 54:20.280
some little didicoy razor gang.
I thought to me self, so what?

54:21.560 --> 54:22.880
But then you fucked me over.

54:23.640 --> 54:26.040
So now you have my undivided attention.

54:28.280 --> 54:30.920
By the way, which one am I talking to?
Who's the boss?

54:32.200 --> 54:35.680
-Well, I'm the oldest.
-Ha! Clearly. (CHUCKLES)

54:36.160 --> 54:37.720
Are you laughing at my brother?

54:40.800 --> 54:43.000
Right. He's the oldest.
You're the thickest.

54:43.080 --> 54:45.560
I'm told the boss is called Tommy,
and I'm guessing that's you,

54:45.720 --> 54:47.720
'cause you're looking me up and down
like I'm a fucking tart.

54:50.640 --> 54:52.120
I want to know what you want.

54:53.480 --> 54:55.720
There were suspicious betting patterns
at Kempton Park.

54:55.800 --> 54:57.160
A horse called Monaghan Boy...

54:58.640 --> 55:00.960
He won by a length twice
and then finished last.

55:01.800 --> 55:03.560
With £3,000 bet on him.

55:04.080 --> 55:05.440
Which one am I talking to?

55:06.880 --> 55:09.760
-Which one of you is the boss?
-I'm Mr Kimber's adviser and accountant.

55:09.880 --> 55:12.960
And I'm the fucking boss, okay?
Right. End of parlay.

55:13.120 --> 55:15.360
You fixed the race
without my permission.

55:16.520 --> 55:19.120
You fucking gypsy scum!

55:19.320 --> 55:23.200
What, live off the war pensions and
these poor old Garrison Lane widows?

55:23.400 --> 55:28.080
That's your level. I am Billy Kimber!
I run the races

55:28.160 --> 55:31.760
and you fixed one of them. So I'm
gonna have you shot against the post.

55:33.560 --> 55:34.760
Mr Kimber.

55:39.320 --> 55:40.400
Look at it.

55:42.240 --> 55:43.480
That has my name in it.

55:44.840 --> 55:46.000
It's from the Lee family.

55:47.800 --> 55:50.520
You are also at war with the Lees,
Mr Kimber, am I right?

55:54.760 --> 55:57.240
The Lees are attacking your bookies
and taking your money.

55:57.480 --> 56:00.640
Your men can't control them.
You need help.

56:02.520 --> 56:04.920
Perhaps we should listen to what
Mr Shelby has to say,

56:06.240 --> 56:07.520
before we make our decisions.

56:09.000 --> 56:10.040
Right. The Lees

56:11.160 --> 56:12.800
are doing a lot of talking at the fairs.

56:12.880 --> 56:14.240
They have a lot of kin.

56:14.320 --> 56:16.320
They're saying the racetracks
are easy meat

56:16.560 --> 56:19.000
because the police are busy
with strikes. Now,

56:19.480 --> 56:21.960
we have connections.
We know how they operate.

56:22.600 --> 56:24.880
You have muscle.

56:25.600 --> 56:28.080
Together we can beat them.
Divided, maybe not.

56:30.640 --> 56:34.440
Mr Kimber, perhaps we should take
some time for reflection.

56:35.080 --> 56:37.840
Possibly make arrangements
for a second meeting.

56:38.600 --> 56:40.120
I admire you, Mr Kimber.

56:41.320 --> 56:45.000
You started with nothing
and built a legitimate business.

56:46.160 --> 56:50.080
It would be an hon our
to work with you, Mr Kimber.

56:52.480 --> 56:56.360
Nobody works "with" me.
People work "for" me.

57:01.560 --> 57:02.680
Pick it up, pikey.

57:13.720 --> 57:15.280
Sit. Sit down.

57:23.880 --> 57:25.000
It's for your ceiling.

57:25.880 --> 57:27.040
Thank you, Mr Kimber.

57:31.520 --> 57:32.600
We will be at Cheltenham.

57:33.920 --> 57:35.000
As will I.

57:54.520 --> 57:55.560
(EXHALES)

57:56.360 --> 57:58.320
So you picked a fight with the Lee's
on purpose.

57:59.080 --> 58:02.800
Tommy, we can't mess with
Billy fucking Kimber.

58:03.240 --> 58:05.240
Get yourself a decent haircut, man.

58:05.640 --> 58:06.880
We're going to the races.

58:29.440 --> 58:35.200
<i># Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track #</i>

58:35.224 --> 58:40.224
http://hiqve.com/
